1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 e6 3. Nc3 d5 4. cxd5 exd5 5. Bg5 Be7 {The Exchange Variation gives White the ideal Pawn skeleton for a minority attack.} 6. e3 O-O 7. Bd3 Nbd7 8. Qc2 Re8 9. Nge2 {A variant from the normal N-B3, making it easier for White to contest K4 and KB5 but more difficult to contest K5.} Nf8 10. O-O {More aggressive, but leaving White fewer options, is the move 10 O-O-O which leads to the Chameleon Variation.} c6 11. Rab1 {Preparing to launch the minority attack with P-QN4, P-QR4 and P-N5.} Bd6 {Threatening 12... BxP ch 13 KxB N-N5 ch 14 K-N1 QxB.} 12. Kh1 Ng6 13. f3 {Debating whether to pursue the minority attack or make a thrust into the center.} Be7 14. Rbe1 {Selecting the central thrust.} Nd7 15. Bxe7 Rxe7 16. Ng3 Nf6 {The Knight cannot be maintained against the advance of the White KP. N/2-B1 was therefore a better defense.} 17. Qf2 Be6 18. Nf5 Bxf5 19. Bxf5 Qb6 20. e4 dxe4 21. fxe4 Rd8 22. e5 {Leaves the QP weak and weakens the square Q5 in order to obtain an advanced outpost and cramp Black.} Nd5 23. Ne4 Nf8 24. Nd6 Qc7 {To prevent N-B8.} 25. Be4 {The alternation of pieces on strong central squares is used here, a technique forcibly espoused by Niemzowitsch.} Ne6 26. Qh4 {Provoking a weakening of the King position.} g6 27. Bxd5 cxd5 28. Rec1 {Occupying the open file to secure a road for the Rook to join the attack.} Qd7 29. Rc3 Rf8 30. Nf5 {If 30... PxN, 31 R-N3 ch N-N2 32 Q-B6 forces mate.} Rfe8 31. Nh6+ {Stronger than the mere win of the Exchange.} Kf8 {If 31... K-N2, 32 Q-B6 ch KxN 33 R-R3 mate.} 32. Qf6 Ng7 33. Rcf3 Rc8 34. Nxf7 Re6 35. Qg5 Nf5 36. Nh6 Qg7 {If 36... K-K1, 37 RxN PxR 38 Q-N8 ch K-K2 39 NxP mate.} 37. g4 {Black resigns, as White's attack is irresistible.} 